                            <p>Based on a recent <strong>Digital Forensics & Incident Response (DFIR)</strong> engagement with a law enforcement agency (LEA) and one of the leading investment organizations in Singapore, Resecurity, Inc. (USA) has uncovered a meaningful link between three major ransomware groups. Resecurity’s HUNTER (HUMINT) unit spotted the <strong>BianLian</strong>, <strong>White Rabbit</strong>, and <strong>Mario </strong>ransomware gangs collaborating in a joint extortion campaign targeting publicly-traded financial services firms. </p>
<p>These cooperative ransom campaigns are rare, but are possibly becoming more common due to the involvement of Initial Access Brokers (IABs) collaborating with multiple groups on the Dark Web. Another factor that may be leading to greater collaboration are law enforcement interventions that create cybercriminal diaspora networks. Displaced participants of these threat actor networks may be more willing to collaborate with rivals. </p>
<p>Still, the growing systemic significance of IABs in the cybercriminal underworld has fomented a more fluid threat landscape where ransomware operators move from one group to another in pursuit of the best financial conditions. Thus, the malicious activity of disparate ransomware gangs may overlap due to the interconnection of varied cybercriminal actors and infrastructures. This is why it is critical to share such intelligence for further analysis with the broader cybersecurity community. </p>
<p> </p>
<h3>Following the White Rabbit</h3>
<p>In the early hours of <strong>July 2<sup>nd</sup>, 2023</strong>, a ransomware victim’s IT infrastructure was paralyzed by the malicious encryption of drives on its Active Directory controller and a cluster of its virtual machines running on VMware ESXi. The company’s technical staff observed a ransomware note with a known signature of the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> ransomware family. This led the IT staff to promptly activate their incident response (IR) procedures. Notably, <strong>White Rabbit</strong>’s ransomware note has historically included a reference to the <strong>Ransomhouse</strong> Telegram Channel. Resecurity observed this familiar trend in the IR engagement described in this report. </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/5840783088537d0399803ce0d3d24ae6.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Independent <a href="https://www.trendmicro.com/en_se/research/22/a/new-ransomware-spotted-white-rabbit-and-its-evasion-tactics.html" rel="nofollow">research</a> conducted by cybersecurity firm Trend Micro noted striking similarities between <strong>White Rabbit</strong>’s signature payload-evasion tactic and the one exhibited by the <strong>Egregor Ransomware</strong> family. Specifically, both ransomware variants feature the use of a command-line password to decrypt their internal configurations and pivot into their ransomware deployments. “This method of hiding malicious activity is a trick that the ransomware family Egregor uses to hide malware techniques from analysis,” according to Trend Micro. Threat actors associated with this ransomware family may be linked to the <strong>FIN8 </strong>cybercrime syndicate, which has been active since 2016, and which is operationally diversified beyond ransomware. </p>
<p>Specifically, <strong>FIN8</strong> has gained notoriety for targeting the insurance, retail, technology, and chemical sectors by compromising point-of-sale (PoS) systems and stealing payment card data. Meanwhile,the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> ransomware family was first <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/new-white-rabbit-ransomware-linked-to-fin8-hacking-group/" rel="nofollow">spotted</a>
in the wild targeting financial institutions (FIs) in December 2021 after it struck a U.S. bank. At the same time, the <strong>Egregor</strong> ransomware gang was making headlines for compromising the world’s largest bookstore retailer, U.S.-based Barnes & Nobles. Threat researchers have also observed similarities between <strong>Egregor</strong>’s password-protected, payload-execution feature and the ones operationalized by the <strong>MegaCortex</strong> and <strong>SamSam</strong>
ransomware families. </p>
<p>After <strong>White Rabbit</strong>’s initial attack campaign in December 2021, speculation <a href="https://threatpost.com/white-rabbit-ransomware-fin8/177703/" rel="nofollow">abounded</a>
in the cybersecurity community that this variant could be a new tool used by <strong>FIN8 </strong>to pivot into the ransomware business. However, Resecurity has not officially confirmed the link between the two. Dovetailing with <strong>White Rabbit</strong>’s debut, <strong>RansomHouse </strong>Data Leak Site (DLS) launched at the same time , announcing their first victims - the Saskatchewan Liquor and Gaming Authority (SLGA) and a German airline support service provider. </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/c242c9e755f10ee043536e91e9283017.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>A member of the popular cybercrime forum <strong>XSS</strong> going by the handle ‘<strong>SnaZ’</strong> claims that <strong>RansomHouse</strong> is only a DLS, as opposed to a fully operational cybercriminal or ransomware syndicate. Yet, at the same time, <strong>RansomHouse</strong> is heavily interconnected with real-world, malicious cyber-incidents. Mentions of the <strong>RansomHouse </strong>brand also feature prominently in the ransom notes associated with at least two ransomware families. The primary purpose of this DLS is to serve as a resource to leak stolen data and urgently coerce victim payments.</p>
<p>Whether <strong>RansomHouse</strong></p>
<p>is responsible for the actual technical work or not, it’s clear the leak site’s activities are enabling and promoting malicious ransomware activity. It is possible the actors behind <strong>RansomHouse</strong> use this “plausibly deniable” DLS approach as an operational security (OPSEC) measure to create distance between the leak site and the real threat actors operating its infrastructure.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/ed85097e9b8aa766299bab3667c108e2.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>According to <strong>Snaz</strong>’s XSS post, <strong>RansomHouse</strong>’s activities may be limited to negotiation with cyber-extortion victims. Typically, ransomware groups prefer to ‘outsource’ the negotiation stage of their attacks to specialists, with the understanding they will share a percentage of any payout with the actors tasked with coercing victim payments. These ransom negotiators extract payment from victims by weaponizing a variety of dirty tricks, including sending anonymous threatening e-mails, making automated robocalls to their executives and partners, preemptively disclosing breaches to regulators, and increasingly resorting to more disturbing tactics like swatting and threatening victims with real-world violence. </p>
<p>Like <strong>Blackcat</strong>, the threat actors behind <strong>White Rabbit </strong>were among the first to implement the practice of four-to-five-day deadlines for victims to pay their ransoms. The note associated with this ransom family threatens to report victims to oversight authorities, which places firms in the crosshairs General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) enforcement and related fines, if they fail to make the extortion payment on time. In the case of our engagement with the victim financial-services (finserv) firm in the Asia-Pacific (APAC) region, Resecurity noted the threat actor’s use of a similar tactic. Specifically, this <strong>White Rabbit</strong> note threatened the victim with a preemptive disclosure of their breach to data protection regulators in Singapore. </p>
<h3>Business Email Compromise to Address Ransom Demand</h3>
<p>Around <strong>July 7<sup>th</sup>, 2023</strong> the executive management of the publicly-traded finserv victim received an email originating from an anonymous threat actor. At the time, it was not clear if this e-mail originated from <strong>White Rabbit</strong> operators or different actors who learned about the incident, or alternatively, separate actors who leveraged the same vulnerabilities to breach the victim’s network. The malicious email originated from a compromised business account that belonged to a maritime logistics company. This attack vector is thus representative of the business email compromise (BEC) typology. </p>
<p>Likely, the threat actors used this tactic to complicate the investigation. Resecurity observed logs available on the e-mail server of another victim, but they were wiped (erased). Other evidence collected by Resecurity revealed an extensive password spraying campaign targeting the victim’s Microsoft Exchange server. Password spraying attacks are a subset of the brute force typology where threat actors run scripts that input the same password or sequence of them on multiple accounts, attempting the process on each account until too many repeated failed login attempts locks users out of the sign-in portal. </p>
<p>The IP addresses associated with this specific campaign primarily originated from China, Taiwan, Thailand, South Korea, and India. Considering the victim’s business was primarily located in Singapore, it’s possible the attackers were primarily targeting financial organizations in the APAC region. This hypothesis could explain why the threat actors’ infrastructure involved compromised network hosts originating from the countries above. </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/5220634eb695dd0680e584d0f621ca40.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p>Resecurity traced the majority of IP addresses used in the password-spraying phase of this ransomware attack cycle to China (294). The next three most prominent jurisdictions ranked in descending order are India (96), Korea (80), and the U.S. (62).</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/e1369a761880ffbb7e5b0bd3c1f460b3.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>

<p>Distribution of hosts by ISP showed dominance of network activity originating from Chinese-based ISPs. Likely, the actor was leveraging a big number of IP address (Residential Proxies) to impersonate legitimate ISP customers from APAC.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/0093f53a643721cd68000f0d999630e4.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>After the initial BEC message, the victim received several additional emails originating from the domains of third-party organizations, the employee accounts of which were compromised for the purpose of extortion-focused communications. Notably, the threat actor remained completely anonymous and didn’t indicate any affiliation with any specific ransomware group. Additionally, no record has emerged on <strong>Ransomhouse</strong>’s Dark Web DLS, despite a reference to the leak-site in the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> ransom note. </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/03f61b41cef29e5e5ff79c927906ed53.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>Ransomhouse Telegram channel, source: Ransomhouse TG</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Around the same time, the victim received several anonymous phone calls with a pre-recorded voicemail threatening them to pay the ransom quickly or see their stock drop. Circling back to ransomware operator tradecraft discussed in the previous section, the threat actors may have recruited a specialized “extortion team” to apply a focused stream of pressure with the aim of coercing victim firm executives to speed up the ransom payment. </p>
<p>Central to the threat actors’ extortion strategy was their focus on the company’s stock price. The attackers also exploited the threat of reputational fallout that risked damaging the victim’s relationships with it clients and partners who were then unaware of the breach and related data theft. </p>

<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/faeb14c281a83fe0684058b489a8b113.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>Anonymous BEC extortion email, source: Resecurity</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>The anonymous threat actor left their contact information to discuss the conditions for ransom payment. Specifically, the extortionists instructed the victim to contact them via TOX (an encrypted TOR-based IM Messenger) or by email at <a href="mailto:swikipedia@onionmail" rel="nofollow">swikipedia@onionmail</a>[.]org. This email service is also designed to operate within the Tor network, offering users the ability to send anonymous and encrypted emails. The victim contacted the threat actors via the TOX ID they provided and received the following payment demands:</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/ca727d9d5c7d7d8ffbac233585e7bc35.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>2022 White Rabbit ransom note, source: Resecurity</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Notably, the message text contains a fragment of the ransom note associated with the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> ransomware family—specifically the one observed in an earlier version of the locker analyzed back in January 2022. The Singapore version doesn’t include any references to the <strong>RansomHouse</strong> Telegram Channel, but it does feature a warning about reporting the incident to law enforcement. </p>

<p>The January 2022 version of the ransom note originally discovered by <a href="https://twitter.com/demonslay335" target="_self" rel="nofollow">Michael Gillespie</a>
also didn’t contain any <a href="https://www.pcrisk.com/removal-guides/22824-white-rabbit-ransomware" rel="nofollow">reference</a>
to <strong>RansomHouse</strong> Telegram channel. But later, threat actors modified the note to include the eference. It remains unclear what motivated the threat actors to incorporate <strong>RansomHouse </strong>into their payment communications. But it’s possible the attackers were pivoting their operations towards a “hack & leak” model.</p>
<p>The threat actor warned the victim not to contact law enforcement and follow the instructions to avoid company IT infrastructure lockdown and further leaking of their data. The attacker demanded that the victim to pay <strong>20 BTC</strong> approximately equal to <strong>$879,554</strong>
(almost $1M considering upward cryptocurrency fluctuations). To demonstrate proof of exfiltration, the threat actor shared a link of the file listing via Sendspace. The listing contained the names of files stolen from Active Directory, Network Storage (NAS), and Virtual Machines environment. </p>
<p>Notably, the e-mail <a href="mailto:swikipedia@onionmail" rel="nofollow">swikipedia@onionmail</a>[.]org shared by the threat actor has been previously <a href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/cybersecurity-advisories/aa23-136a" rel="nofollow">attributed</a>
to <strong>BianLian </strong>ransomware. A joint cybersecurity <a href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/cybersecurity-advisories/aa23-136a" rel="nofollow">advisory</a>
published by the Cybersecurity Infrastructure and Security Agency (CISA) in partnership with the Australian Cyber Security Center (ACSC) in May 2023 warned about this threat actor group. According to the CISA-ACSC advisory, “<strong>BianLian</strong>
is a ransomware developer, deployer, and data extortion cybercriminal group that has targeted organizations in multiple U.S. critical infrastructure sectors since June 2022. They have also targeted Australian critical infrastructure sectors in addition to professional services and property development.” </p>
<p>The advisory also notes the following about the group: <strong>BianLian</strong> “gains access to victim systems through valid Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) credentials, uses open-source tools and command-line scripting for discovery and credential harvesting, and exfiltrates victim data via File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Rclone, or Mega. BianLian group actors then extort money by threatening to release data if payment is not made. BianLian group originally employed a double-extortion model in which they encrypted victims’ systems after exfiltrating the data; however, around January 2023, they shifted to primarily exfiltration-based extortion.”</p>
<h3>Dark Web Communications – Public Relations of Ransomware Groups in Action</h3>
<p>The victim received over 11 anonymous emails threatening to release their data. The victim chose to ignore the email threats. Threat actors retaliated to the victim’s non-engagement with them by posting a full listing of their stolen data on the Dark Web, including multiple samples. A threat actor using the alias “<strong>Paulsan</strong>” authored this post on July 29, 2023. This listing was identical to the one previously shared with victim directly via Sendspace. The actor warned the victim that they planned to release all of their data if payment was not made within five days. </p>
<p>The exposure of actual stolen documents and the possible release of the entire data set intensified the gravity of the situation for the victim. This was likely the main goal the threat actor intended to achieve by posting the negotiation listings and samples on the Dark Web. But at that time, it was not clear if “<strong>Paulsan</strong>” was related to <strong>White Rabbit</strong> or <strong>Ransomhouse</strong>. However, it was readily apparent that the posting of victim data on the Dark Web was related to the same extortion chain.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/ac601701171fccc8084808ef4e3e7288.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>Paulsan posts sample of victim Singapore investment holding company data, source: XSS</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Notably, two months before the attack, this threat actor was aiming to monetize 110 GB stolen from a U.S.-based transportation companies via several Dark Web communities.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/b3214f522c7c35a2f5c3e56d3a7c0bbb.png" data-image="file-0"></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>Thus, <strong>Paulsan</strong> may be an IAB or affiliate that supports ransomware operations by publicizing samples of stolen data via the Dark Web, to exert additional pressure on victim and coerce them to pay the ransom faster.</p>
<h3>Mario Ransomware seconds White Rabbit.</h3>
<p>Based on further investigation, several affected of the victim’s affected hosts also contained new ransomware notes with a signature attributed to <strong>Mario </strong>ransomware. Like the note left by <strong>White Rabbit</strong>, the note also contained a direct reference to the <strong>RansomHouse </strong>Telegram Channel. This link between the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> and <strong>Mario </strong>lockers with <strong>RansomHouse </strong>DLS remained opaque at the time, however. </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/e75dd97520dbac6fc7319cbf76da9266.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>Italian Mario Ransomware note, source: MalwareHunterTeam</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>In one of the ransom notes <a href="https://twitter.com/malwrhunterteam/status/1560327142621208577/" rel="nofollow">observed</a>
by independent researchers from MalwareHunterTeam, who were analyzing an attacking on a victim in Italy, attributed both <strong>White Rabbit</strong> and <strong>Mario Ransomware</strong> to the incident. Notably, the note was specifically related to a locker version designed to target VMware ESXi. It’s possible the developers of the Windows and ESXi-based lockers are different. Yet, these threat actors may still collaborate when attacking different IT systems. Notably, the early versions of <strong>Mario </strong>ransomware for ESXi were based on <strong>Babuk Ransomware</strong>’s <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/babuk-code-used-by-9-ransomware-gangs-to-encrypt-vmware-esxi-servers/#google_vignette" rel="nofollow">leaked source</a>.  </p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/b9faf20f92cabb2ea9663a96a8f8a5b9.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>Italian White Rabbit ransomware note, source: MalwareHunterTeam</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>The relationship between the three ransomware gangs started to become clear on <strong>June 30, 2023</strong>, when Resecurity DFIR team acquired logs that confirmed a successful password spraying attack on several Microsoft Exchange email accounts used by the victim firm’s employees. This attack leveraging multiple Residential IP Proxies based in in APAC region. On <strong>July 2, 2023</strong>, the threat actor successfully breached three employees’ mailboxes were, providing the attacker with access to critical IT and operational documents. The attackers gained a foothold into the victim’s network by exploiting an outdated VPN solution used by the company, Any Connect ASA 5506X, which had reached its end-of-life in July 2022. This VPN compromise paved the way for the subsequent ransomware attack. </p>
<p>The attack campaign crescendoed on <strong>July 4, 2023</strong>, between 3:20 AM and 4:30 AM, as multiple VMware ESX servers hosting eight virtual servers succumbed to the <strong>Mario Ransomware</strong> strain. Simultaneously, two physical PCs fell prey to a <strong>White Rabbit </strong>infection. It was not clear why the attackers leveraged multiple ransomware families within the same IT infrastructure, but considering both have ties to RansomHouse, it is possible they were developed by the same actors or related ones. Post infection, the victim’s virtual server partitions were fully encrypted, impeding any analysis of potential data exfiltration. Intriguingly, data from the affected PCs hinted at unauthorized access via a VM Server, coupled with the execution of OneDrive just before the <strong>White Rabbit</strong> strain encrypted the data.</p>

<p>On<strong> September 8</strong>, <strong>2023</strong>, the threat actors made good on their threats by publishing a 600 GB evidence pack on <strong>Ransomhouse</strong>’s TOR-based DLS. Notably, it included the same file listing previously shared by “<strong>Paulsen</strong>” on the Dark Web.</p>

<h3>Timeline of the Incident</h3>
<p>The timeline of this incident confirms a strong connection between the threat actors involved in the activity of the <strong>White Rabbit</strong>, Mario, and <strong>BianLian</strong> ransomware groups. Almost a three- months-long campaign resulted in a targeted, persistent assault on the victim’s IT infrastructure. The patience and persistence of this campaign confirms that the actors behind it were experienced in the nuances of extorting high-value victims. These threat actors operated like seasoned professionals and never rushed the extortion process. </p>

<h3>Forensic Challenges and Limited Visibility</h3>
<p>The fallout of this incident posed significant challenges for investigators. While Resecurity investigators were able to live boot the victim’s servers, the locker’s encryption rendered the 2.4 TB SAS drives inaccessible. The locker thus hindered Resecurity investigators’ attempts to mount the virtual data store of VMDK files. The absence of syslog and artifacts compounded the difficulties in tracing the malware's execution path.</p>
<p>As organizations grapple with today’s rapidly evolving ransomware threat landscape, this case illustrates the critical importance of proactive cybersecurity strategy and planning. These security provisions should include regular system updates, robust threat detection mechanisms, and employee training to help personnel identify and prevent social engineering attacks. Additionally, this attack further illustrates the <a href="https://www.privatefundscfo.com/a-matter-of-trust-why-your-vpn-falls-short/" rel="nofollow">vulnerability</a>
of VPNs to ransomware attackers. These perimeter-based security solutions, which are essentially encrypted tunnels that enable remote employees to connect to the enterprise network, are a favored target for ransomware actors. As such, VPNs have become increasingly unsuitable for the finserv sector.</p>
<p>In the place of VPNs, zero-trust network access (ZTNA) solutions have become increasingly popular in the finserv sector. Unlike single-tunnel VPNs, zero-trust architectures deny access to all network resources by default, even if users are already inside the security perimeter.  Additionally, the triple-extortion tactics employed in this incident also underscore why organizations should expand their cyber-threat intelligence (CTI) collection. At the same time, enterprises need to craft and implement a comprehensive cybersecurity strategy to mitigate the impact of increasingly collaborative ransomware campaigns.<br></p>
<h3>A multi-actor “Ransomware Fraternity?”</h3>
<p>Beyond the threat actors discussed in this report, other marquee players in the ransomware ecosystem have recently made public overtures for intergroup collaboration. Resecurity recently observed the potential continuation of this trend following law enforcement’s apparent disruption of <strong>ALPHV</strong>
(BlackCat’s) ransomware infrastructure and the <strong>NoEscape</strong> ransomware group’s exit scam. On <strong>December 11, 2023</strong>, a <strong>RAMP </strong>cybercriminal forum account associated with the <strong>LockBit </strong>ransomware gang offered to share the gang’s Dark Web DLS infrastructure with displaced <strong>ALPHV</strong> and <strong>NoEscape </strong>affiliates in the forum chat.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/3eec94a8b116ce3a6ee7587b95d3b98c.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>LockBit offers their DLS to displaced ransomware affiliates so they can resume victim negotiations, source: RAMP</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>LockBit’s </strong>proposition has inspired animated discussion in the forum chat, attracting the attention of a threat actor who goes by the handle “<strong>BlackCat46</strong>,” who is high-reputation member of the ALPHV ransomware gang.</p>
<figure><img src="https://www.resecurity.com/uploads/post/232/5fed1d4231c1134ef87803f27b35270b.png" data-image="file-0"><figcaption>LockBit philosophizes on RAMP source: RAMP</figcaption></figure>
<p><br></p>
<p>On <strong>December 14, 2023</strong>, <strong>BlackCat46 </strong>responded: “On the one hand, I see that this is hype and benefit for you. but on the other hand, it’s noticeable that you’re handing it over.” To this comment, <strong>LockBit </strong>replied in a series of chat messages: “ransomware fraternity). Alone we will perish, together we will survive.” LockBit has thus far concluded their chat thread by asserting that if  “all the special services of the world unite in the fight against us, we must unite in the fight against them.”</p>
<p>It remains to be seen how LockBit’s proposition to various ransomware refugees will unfold. However, this development further illustrates Resecurity’s warning about the growing threat of cooperative ransomware campaigns. It is an interesting dynamic to see various ransomware groups, such as <strong>White Rabbit</strong>, <strong>Mario</strong>, and <strong>BianLian</strong>, collaborating and joining forces. We will continue to monitor these groups closely, as they currently represent the major players in the ransomware ecosystem on the dark web. As the cybersecurity community shares intelligence and resources, they must also provision for an emerging threat landscape where ransomware attackers and other cybercriminal actors do the same.</p>
<p>On <strong>December 18</strong>, the Securities and Exchange Commission's (SEC) <a rel="nofollow">new disclosure requirements</a> go into effect and will require public companies to publicly report material cybersecurity incidents within four days of making a determination that an incident is material. Resecurity is expecting major ransomware groups to accelerate attacks against publicly-traded organizations specifically with the spike of activity during holidays season.</p>
